# Courseforge SHACL Rules v1 — Phase 5 (RDF/SHACL enrichment)
#
# This file hosts SHACL-AF *rules* (sh:TripleRule, sh:SPARQLRule) that
# DERIVE typed-edge triples for the Trainforge concept graph. It is
# intentionally separate from courseforge_v1.shacl.ttl (which holds
# validation-only Core constraints) so that rule firing and constraint
# checking can be reasoned about independently:
#
#   * courseforge_v1.shacl.ttl       — validation only (no sh:rule)
#   * courseforge_v1.shacl-rules.ttl — derivation only (sh:rule on every shape)
#
# The rules are gated at runtime by the TRAINFORGE_USE_SHACL_RULES env
# var (see Trainforge/rag/shacl_rule_runner.py). Default off — the
# Python rules under Trainforge/rag/inference_rules/ remain canonical
# until equivalence is proven across the corpus.
#
# Predicate identity reuses the Phase 2.1 vocabulary
# (schemas/context/courseforge_v1.vocabulary.ttl) — no parallel
# predicates are minted.

@prefix rdf:    <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#> .
@prefix rdfs:   <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
@prefix sh:     <http://www.w3.org/ns/shacl#> .
@prefix xsd:    <http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#> .
@prefix ed4all: <https://ed4all.dev/ns/courseforge/v1#> .

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Phase 5.1 — `defined-by` derivation (proof-of-concept)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# Python rule of record:
#   Trainforge/rag/inference_rules/defined_by_from_first_mention.py
#
# Semantics: for every Concept node carrying one or more
# ed4all:occurrence triples (the inverted-index back-references to
# chunks that mention the concept), derive a single
# ed4all:isDefinedBy triple pointing at the first occurrence by
# ASC sort over the chunk-IRI lexicographic order. Concepts with
# zero occurrences produce no edge.
#
# Why sh:SPARQLRule instead of sh:TripleRule:
#
#   sh:TripleRule's node expressions support paths, filters, and
#   sub-shapes but no ORDER BY / LIMIT (corpus chunk_00181, cache
#   query q_20260426_205717_834f3a35). First-occurrence-by-sort
#   requires SPARQL row ordering and bounding, which only a
#   CONSTRUCT/WHERE body can express.
#
# Equivalence with the Python rule is asserted by
# Trainforge/tests/test_shacl_rules_defined_by.py.

ed4all:DefinedByRule
  a sh:NodeShape ;
  rdfs:label "DefinedByRule" ;
  rdfs:comment "Phase 5.1 SHACL-AF derivation rule: emits one ed4all:isDefinedBy edge per Concept whose ed4all:occurrence values are non-empty, picking the lex-min chunk IRI as the first-mention. Equivalent to Trainforge/rag/inference_rules/defined_by_from_first_mention.py under TRAINFORGE_USE_SHACL_RULES=true." ;
  sh:targetClass ed4all:Concept ;
  sh:rule [
    a sh:SPARQLRule ;
    rdfs:label "defined_by_from_first_mention" ;
    sh:order 0 ;
    sh:prefixes ed4all: ;
    sh:construct """
      PREFIX ed4all: <https://ed4all.dev/ns/courseforge/v1#>
      CONSTRUCT { $this ed4all:isDefinedBy ?firstChunk . }
      WHERE {
        {
          SELECT $this (MIN(?occ) AS ?firstChunk)
          WHERE {
            $this ed4all:occurrence ?occ .
          }
          GROUP BY $this
        }
      }
    """ ;
  ] .

# Note on the SPARQL body:
#
# The SHACL-AF spec requires CONSTRUCT bodies to contain only the
# CONSTRUCT/WHERE clauses (no top-level ORDER BY / LIMIT modifiers
# on the outer query). To pick the lex-min ?occ deterministically,
# we wrap the WHERE inner pattern in a sub-SELECT with `MIN(?occ)`
# and `GROUP BY $this`. SPARQL's MIN over xsd:string-typed (or IRI-
# typed) values is lex-order — byte-identical to Python's
# `sorted(occurrences)[0]` on ASCII chunk-IDs.
#
# `sh:prefixes ed4all:` declares the namespace used in the body.
# pyshacl's advanced=True path resolves this against the ontology
# header it imports along with the shapes graph.
